# Commit Conventions (Conventional Commits)

This project uses **semantic-release** with **Conventional Commits** to automate versioning and changelogs.

## Commit Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <short description>
```

`scope` is optional. Keep the subject line under 72 characters.

## Types and Their Version Impact

| Type | Version Bump | Use When |
|------|-------------|----------|
| `feat` | **minor** (0.x.0) | Adding new functionality |
| `fix` | **patch** (0.0.x) | Fixing a bug |
| `perf` | **patch** | Performance improvement |
| `docs` | no release | Documentation only |
| `chore` | no release | Tooling, deps, CI, config |
| `test` | no release | Adding or updating tests |
| `refactor` | no release | Code change with no feature/fix |
| `style` | no release | Formatting, whitespace |
| `ci` | no release | CI/CD changes |

## Breaking Changes → Major Bump

Add `BREAKING CHANGE:` in the commit body or `!` after the type:

```
feat!: remove deprecated setHeaders API

BREAKING CHANGE: setHeaders has been removed, use setHeaderMapper instead.
```

## Examples

```
feat(core): add request streaming support
fix(react): prevent stale closure in useFetch callback
test(sockets): add WebSocket reconnection specs
chore: migrate build system to Vite
refactor(adapter): simplify payload mapping logic
docs: update cache invalidation guide
```

## Rules

- One logical change per commit — don't mix features with refactors
- Use imperative mood: "add feature" not "added feature"
- Reference issues when relevant: `fix(core): resolve timeout race condition (#123)`
- Never use `feat` or `fix` for changes that don't affect published packages (use `chore` or `test`)
